            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-12-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-01-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="109" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d109">
                <head>109. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The first meeting of the Development Assistance Group was held in Washington,
                    March 9–11. Japan, Belgium, Canada, France, the Federal Republic of Germany,
                    Italy, Portugal, the <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss>, the United Kingdom,
                    and the United States were represented at the meeting. Discussions of the
                    objectives of the group took place. A second meeting of the <gloss
                        target="#t_DAG1">DAG</gloss> was held in Bonn July 5–7. The Netherlands
                    joined the <gloss target="#t_DAG1">DAG</gloss> for discussions which centered on
                    the forms of credit which the industrialized nations should extend to the
                    underdeveloped states. A third meeting of the <gloss target="#t_DAG1"
                        >DAG</gloss> took place in Washington October 3–5. Discussions centered
                    around technical assistance for economic development policies and planning, the
                    operations of capital lending institutions, the roles of national and
                    international organizations in providing aid, and the coordination of
                    pre-investment technical assistance activities. The Development Assistance Group
                    became part of the <gloss target="#t_OECD1">OECD</gloss> after the conclusion of
                    the convention of December 14. Documentation on the <gloss target="#t_DAG1"
                        >DAG</gloss> is in Department of State, <gloss target="#t_EUR1"
                    >EUR</gloss>/RPE Files: Lot 62 D 754, Development Assistance Group.</p>
            </div>
